    <title>Combined summary - Coins: A trustless sidechain protocol</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T23:15:57.738587+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-January/017567.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In discussions on the Bitcoin development mailing list, experts are exploring potential solutions to address Bitcoin's scalability and security issues. One proposed solution is a bitcoin-backed proof-of-stake (PoS) sidechain protocol called Coins that allows for arbitrary sidechain assets. The proposal suggests using networks of thousands of anonymous altcoins built around Bitcoin as the central settlement layer to increase scalability. However, some experts express concerns about the security of PoS sidechains and their reliance on a limited number of sophisticated actors willing to run full nodes.Other proposed solutions include using channel factories instead of sidechains, which allow for payments at scale and can support changes to the channel topology to scale. While Lightning Network works well under certain conditions, it may not be suitable for the next billion users who do not have reliable internet connections or funds to manage channels' inbound capacity.There is also a discussion on the use of non-interactive channels to solve the problem of one-sided opens. The suggestion is made to use channel factories instead of sidechains, but it is unclear if this would provide an offline-like participation user experience without registration with any gateway provider.Overall, while there are different proposals and discussions on how to improve the scalability and security of Bitcoin, the consensus is that the current custodial solutions are not sustainable in the long run, and the community should work towards developing trustless and decentralized solutions like sidechains.</summary>
